column260: (1) My confidence in the IT department to build and manage secure networks, systems, and applications is limited. / (2) The IT department relies largely on products from untrustworthy corporate vendors, notably Apple and Microsoft. Microsoft has proved time and again that none of its products can be considered secure, and we now know that both of these companies, among others, willingly introduced backdoors into their products for the purpose of government surveillance. / (3) UofM Secure is the only of the three primary 802.11 networks which is encrypted, but it is totally unusable during peak hours, at least in Tate lab, where I work.
column277: (1) The very first priority needs to be improving the UofM Secure infrastructure so that it can provide fast, reliable connections everywhere on campus and during peak hours. Unencrypted connections are totally unacceptable, and there are too many places on campus where cellular reception is poor or nonexistent to justify not providing WiFi. / (2) The website's mobile format needs to be expanded to include much more than it does, for example, all of the course scheduling pages on OneStop. Also, the webpages need to be changed to present the information that people actually want; for example, OneStop should default to Home instead of News. / (3) Dependence of University webpages on JavaScript should be reduced as much as possible. It is a security concern, and I do not necessarily consider the University's sites secure or trustworthy enough to enable such functionality blindly. Note that some University pages default to desktop forms when JavaScript is disabled, even on mobile devices. / (4) Improve the University's website in general. http://xkcd.com/773

column277: As a theatre student, I spend most of my time on campus in the basement of the Marshall Performing Arts Center, as do most students in my major.  There is currently a bare minimum of wireless phone service available to us, and most of us cannot receive service at all.  Theatre students are very busy and most of our meetings deal with larger groups of people.  We need to be able to communicate quickly and effectively, as an unexpected change in schedule can affect large groups of people.  Such changes could include a professor being late to class and needing a TA to take over for a few minutes, or a student needing to reschedule a costume fitting, or a group meeting to rehearse a scene.  One of the most valuable things a theatre major can have is their ability to communicate efficiently.  We currently do not have this ability, and while the lack of wireless service hasn't caused any train wrecks, there have been numerous occasions when having adequate cell phone service would have saved time and worry.  I feel that before the university focuses on improving the online tools available to students on their mobile phones, they should first focus on making sure that students can actually access those tools.

column159: This is the most important thing I'd like implemented on mobile
column160: The organization is so different on mobile than a laptop, it's very difficult to find things, and quite a lot of what's visible isn't what I want. Some amount of customization might be helpful -- I usually only access Moodle with my mobile device to 1) check grades (which I haven't been able to locate on mobile), 2) check due dates, or 3) check forum posts by professors. If I had the option to toggle off all other content but that, I likely would.
column164: I have Kindle on both my laptop and mobile, and I use quite a few e-books instead of purchasing the textbooks, so utilize my mobile device to check on text, read on the bus, etc. Having access to videos we have to watch for assignments on Moodle mobile is great, too -- I can plug in my earphones at lunch or on the bus to let it play in the background. I use Google Drive and Dropbox frequently -- I store my syllabi, assignments, and other documents there for easy access, so I can pull them up and glance at them whenever I need to confirm an assignment description, due date, etc. It's quicker to edit documents on a laptop, but I wouldn't mind doing so via mobile (though it would likely only be superficial edits, rather than larger content-creation)
column259: No, I do not have security concerns using my mobile on campus
column275: I did not use Google Drive as extensively before grad school, I've really been converted to using it almost exclusively for all needs.
column276: Discovering I could download a Kindle app and get many of my textbooks as e-books was phenomenal, because I can carry several of my textbooks with me at all times and read a few pages whenever I have some downtime. I fiddled around for a while with finding a text-to-speech program that could read PDF articles, so I could play my PDFs through my car speakers when driving long distances, or have bring headphones and have my phone read the PDFs aloud, but most of the text-to-speech programs available are designed for people with disabilities and require shifting your mobile settings to accessibility standards. Some PDFs were image files rather than text, but a decent OCR program can solve that.

column119: A moodle app would be extremely helpful. I find moodle to be fairly inconvenient as I try to limit the amount of time I spend on my computer and truthfully, the internet is a distracting place. While the moodle mobile site is fairly usable for checking assignments and logistical questions about classes on the go, it still presents inconveniences that could be avoided if professors were to actually go over due dates/assignments in class rather than leaving it up to moodle. The mobile site requires a tedious log-in (as does gmail.umn.edu).  An app could have you constantly logged in an enable push notifications to alert you of upcoming assignments, new assignments that are posted, changes to syllabuses, and even alert you when a class has been cancelled. Also communication on moodle is poor at best. Posting to a forum is likely to get a response much too late, and it may not even receive a satisfactory answer. Somebody may know the answer, but never see the post as it is unrealistic to constantly be on moodle. It'd be most convenient to be alerted when you actually need to look, rather than a guess and check method. Forum posts could allow instant communication to anyone with the app, as they'd be notified immediately, including staff.

column160: Really an app would be ideal. As is the mobile site works fine for checking a syllabus or a due date real quick, but isn't much better than a computer. Being permanently logged in would be helpful with the app (you can password protect apps) so I don't see much of a security flaw. /  / P.S. Awhile back I saw there was a moodle app created but I  neglected getting it as it had a 1/5 star rating. After writing this I reviewed the comments on it and it seems nobody could get it to work, but the few that did found it helpful. I'll be testing out this app, but this should be something more heavily advertised if it's any good, with more clear instructions on getting it to function.

column119: Right now we use Cengage or other 3rd party websites that have no support for a mobile version whatsoever. This means that when I go study or get school work done I have to lug around my laptop instead of simply bringing my iPad. The iPad is much better than a laptop because it has a better camera for taking and uploading photos for assignments, it's easier to use, has a better battery life (helpful in coffee shops where plug-ins aren't available), and it is much more portable. I would like to eventually see the U of M switch to an all-mobile program (if one exists) so that we literally don't have to use a computer for anything and can do everything from our tablets. /  / It would also be nice to be able to at least check on these 3rd party sites from our smartphones. Right now it isn't possible. It would be great because we would be able to check due dates and grades on the go.

column260: I work within the AHC and students, residents, and faculty all remotely access our electronic health record via mobile devices. column276: I use my phone to take photos of slides on the projector if I cannot write notes fast enough. That way, I have it on my phone and later transfer the information from the picture into my notes. It helps me be able to listen in class and not be distracted by frantically taking notes, and it also reinforces what I've learned to copy the notes down later.
column277: I think the biggest frustration I've had with using my mobile device on campus is that wi fi connection can be inconsistent. I'm almost always able to access wi fi, but my phone never connects instantly to campus wi fi, even though I use it every day. I always have to sign in. And it doesn't always stay connected after I've signed in. If I move locations, I always have to sign in all over again. While it's not the end of the world, obviously, it is frustrating to waste time signing into a network that should connect instantly to my phone and stay connected.

column160: I believe that it would make things easier and make Moodle just more accessible and people will be able to use it more times than if they are operating off their laptop, or something that is not exactly portable and can be hand-held.
